Definitely more step-by step. Instead of letting things sit a lot more in my head and waiting for a joke to magically pop out, I could use these strategies to help me think of things.

Yes. The aspects and associations ideas were most helpful. I could easily generate a bunch of different types of jokes from the subject matter those techniques helped me generate. The sarcasm / angle violations were also useful.
Definitely the aspects and associations tools. It generates a bunch of great ideas for a joke and makes it much easier to finish them with either the other techniques or just by thinking.
It was sometimes hard to remember all the vocabulary and how to use each tool, but that's more a factor of the length of the study it seemed to me. With more time I'd probably have had better memory.
Yes definitely! It's super cool, both in that it helps you make jokes, and also in that it helps you learn more about humor, language, and psychology.

It was way easier, I actually had some techniques for figuring out a funny angle on the titles. It felt cool to try to put those into action rather than just think "hm maybe I'm not funny."

Yes! I used the associations a lot, I found them really helpful for finding a new angle or a way to be sarcastic because I could very quickly put the headline in a new context and contrast it with things that might make it seem ridiculous. I used the violations because I knew that I had two choices -- helped to narrow it down and make it feel manageable. I used the expected reactions and expected beliefs because they helped me to be sarcastic more intentionally - I could use them to make sure the jokes violated expectations.

Before, I was trying to think, I know there is something funny here...especially about the primate. But I was at a loss. Maybe if I had a few hours to mull it over I would have arrived at something. But the tutorial made it so that I could fire off a bunch of possibilities and hone in on what I felt was funny about it. I felt that I could express my own sense of humor better, even though I was using general techniques.
The beliefs (e.g., pos/neg) were not so useful because I couldn't remember them, or really understand how to use them. I didn't really get that part.

Yes, I think it's fun! In the end, it felt cool to be able to write a joke. I'd like to show a friend and then compare jokes, that would be cool. It's a neat form of self-expression. I used to think being funny was just some talent some people had, but it's neat that you can work at it.
